mb|p|nt| 
hondo717: Let me also discuss an alternative response when partner bids 2NT over your weak 2.  Many people play 2NT asks for a feature, an outside A or K  and that is a reasonable way to play. I prefer, however. another convention known as "Ogust." With Ogust, the weak 2 bidder describes 2 characteristics about his hand. Whether he has a good hand (8-10 HCP) or a bad hand (5-7 HCP) and : and whether he has a good suit (2 of the top 3 honors) or a bad suit (not 2 of the top 3 honors.)  Ogust works as follows. If partner bids 2NT, you respond as follows: |
pg| ***** 107 ***** |


mb|2H|nt|
hondo717: if you have the best hand you can have, a "good hand" (8-10) and "good suit", you bid 3@S, if you have a "good hand" but bad suit, you bid  3@H and  if you have the worst hand you can have, (a "bad hand" (5-7) and a "bad suit"), you bid 3@C, the lowest bid.  Finally, you bid 3@D  and if you have a bad hand but a good suit. |
pg| ***** 108 ***** |


nt|
hondo717: So basically, Ogust allows you to open a weak 2 with a wide variety of hands, and partner still has a way of finding out what type of weak 2 you are bidding.  Usually, responder needs one honor in your suit, and at least an opening hand  to bid 2NT over your weak 2 opening.  |
